ht to know leads to the indiscriminate investigation and dissemination of secrets. Consequently, in her view, the theoretical ideal of the public sphere, in which all processes are transparent, reduces real-world politics to the drama of the secret and its discovery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCulture. 0aPolitical science. 0aPublicity. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Media & Internet .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172123640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501721236423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501721236/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK